objects.name: Damballa, Inc.
objects.description: Publisher and author of the report. Damballa Threat Research discovered and analyzed the IMDDOS Botnet using a globe-spanning array of DNS sensors and automated clustering/machine learning systems. Damballa is headquartered in Atlanta and focuses on stopping crimeware and botnets.

objects.name: imddos malware
objects.description: Executable used by the IMDDOS Botnet to infect host PCs and participate in DDoS operations. Upon execution it self-installs (auto set-up), copies itself to the Windows system32 folder, and renames to six random-character filenames. It achieves persistence by modifying registry Services subkeys at HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services, registering as a Service named SafePrec<xxx>, and obfuscating its ImagePath by encoding the file path in hexadecimal (e.g., C:\WINDOWS\system32\goemka.exe). The malware connects to a Target-List Hosting Domain (TLHD) at imddos.my03.com:9090 (and test.dns-dns.com:9090 during testing) to fetch a PREDEFINED HTML file containing target domains (e.g., puff.html, test1.html, 888.html, bawang.html, gesheng.html, 090210.html, 2764485.html, chinawf518.html, xiaonan888.html). It then checks for updates to the target list, validates targets via IP connections, and communicates with dynamic CnC domains, sending host information (OS, CPU speed, memory) in plain text for asset selection. When remotely triggered, it launches DDoS attacks against specified targets. Samples share characteristics: no rootkit technology, not packed, and plaintext communications. It uses distinct user-agent identifiers to cluster variants (e.g., STORMDDOS, YTDDOS, IAMDDOS, i am ddos, kav). Network behavior is noisy, regularly querying TLHD, CnC, and target domains (about three requests every two seconds) and repeatedly looping even if resources are down.

objects.name: IMDDOS service provider
objects.description: A criminal organization based in China that operates the IMDDOS Botnet as a commercial DDoS-as-a-service offering. It registered malicious domains beginning March 20, 2010, and promotes its service via an IMDDOS website. The business model includes free and paid tiers (monthly, annually, lifetime) with 24x7 support for lifetime customers, sales and support via QQ chat, and recruitment of resale agents. Customers can also rent servers from the provider’s pool. Architecturally, a single entity (bot master) controls the Target-List Hosting Domain (TLHD) and PREDEFINED HTML target lists, while multiple, largely unrelated CnC domains (mostly via 3322.org dynamic DNS) enable a rental infrastructure for different bot operators. TTPs include controlling targets centrally via TLHD, managing dynamic CnC, collecting host OS/CPU/memory to allocate assets for attacks, and the ability to disable segments by removing target lists or DDoS non-paying operators by updating targets. Primary goal is monetized DDoS attacks against customer-specified domains.

objects.name: 3322.org
objects.description: A popular dynamic DNS provider based in China that hosted most IMDDOS CnC domains, facilitating command-and-control operations for the botnet.

objects.name: QQ
objects.description: A Chinese chat service used by the IMDDOS service provider for sales inquiries, customer support, and discussion groups.
